I agree with you, but you have to take into consideration that Everquest has an established background and setting.  If you want your character to be a dark elf that follows Tunare, you may... but there should be a penalty of some sort for going against &quot;the way the world should be.&quot;  In a &quot;normal&quot; RP game, those penalities can come from the person running the game, or other players.  In EQ though, there is really no one running things, and players have limited options to cause repucussions.  (I dont believe training someone or the like is acceptable behavior... other then breaking the rules, there is little one player can do to affect another negativly.)<br>
<br>
That is what I feel the exp rules accomplished.  They made it more difficult to be the &quot;odd&quot; character, which it should be.  If there is no &quot;norm&quot; and everyone is some special instance, the entire setting become muddled and worthless.<br>
<br>
