<br>
If you play a star trek role playing game, would it be acceptable for someone to play an tolkien elf?<br>
<br>
It's not about forcing an individual's vision onto anyone, its about creating a story that meshes with the world as it's presented.  Some people wont do that, such as the &quot;drow&quot; types, and that's fine.  Some of them are pretty good RP'ers, and I just sort of glaze my eyes over their language and move on with the RP.  That's ok too.<br>
<br>
But, the history and background of EQ exists and can not just be ignored.  If you do that, you aren't really RP'ing in the same world as everyone else.  Of course, no one can stop you... but I know personally I just try to move past people who insist on breaking continuity.  Im not rude about it, but they just arent a part of my story.  I treat doodz the same way.<br>
<br>
Can you be a &quot;good&quot; dark elf?  Sure why not, does that somehow fall outside of the established material?  Can you be a &quot;evil&quot; paladin follower of Inny?  No, you can't.  It violates the &quot;rules&quot; of the world and setting and just doesnt make sense.<br>
<br>
People don't like restrictions, but they do exist.  There is a history and background to the world and it shouldnt be ignored just because you dont like it.<br>
<br>
On a slightly off topic note, why would this thread be closed?  Even if its come up before, no one is being nasty and I think some people are enjoying talking about it, even if they disagree.  I don't think disliking the topic should be grounds for thread removal. &lt;shrug&gt; <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">~Vabris Vy'Tok, of House Vy'Tok~<br>
